- Feedback extraction candidates
    - format: per candidate, list chapter, location, paraphrase, situation, outcome
    - outcomes: → promoted to <slug>, → folded into <slug>, → dropped because <reason>

- Chapter 2: Introduction (From Push to Pull), lines 290-470

    - candidate: pull-not-push reroute
        - location: lines 367-386, "Pull Beats Push" section
        - paraphrase: when you notice yourself cataloguing the giver's incompetence, reroute attention to what the receiver can pull from the exchange. The receiver controls intake, sense-making, and change, so leverage lives there.
        - situation: you are receiving feedback you find poorly delivered, off base, or from someone you do not respect, and your mind is composing a list of their inadequacies (Tom's drive home, line 399).
        - outcome: → promoted to pull-not-push-reroute

    - candidate: receiving-well-is-not-accepting
        - location: lines 423-428, "The Benefits of Receiving Well" opening
        - paraphrase: receiving well means engaging the conversation skillfully and making thoughtful choices about whether and how to use the feedback. It is not the same as taking the feedback. Sorting the two prevents the false binary of swallow-or-shut-out.
        - situation: you are about to dismiss feedback because it is wrong, or about to swallow it whole because refusing would mean you are defensive. You feel forced to pick.
        - outcome: → promoted to engaging-is-not-accepting

    - candidate: hold-both-needs (learn AND be accepted)
        - location: lines 392-417, "The Tension Between Learning and Being Accepted"
        - paraphrase: the discomfort of feedback comes from the collision of two real, simultaneous needs — to learn/improve and to be accepted as you are. Naming both reduces the pressure to collapse one into the other.
        - situation: you feel an outsized reaction to mild feedback ("why can't you just accept me?") or you intellectualize the feedback and then bristle later. The self-acceptance need is hidden under the learning conversation, or vice versa.
        - outcome: → promoted to name-both-needs

    - candidate: "feedback is any information about yourself" (broad definition)
        - location: lines 343-351, "What Counts As Feedback?"
        - paraphrase: feedback includes formal evaluations and the implicit signals (the friend slipping off the gift sweater, the renewal of services, the bum knee). Widen the aperture.
        - outcome: → dropped because the broadened-definition observation does not yield a distinct receiver-side action with its own signal and failure mode. It is a frame the rest of the book operates inside, parent-context material.

    - candidate: brief history of feedback
        - location: lines 356-369
        - paraphrase: the term comes from mechanical/electronic systems and got transplanted to people; the model that produces "tighten up here, dial back there" is the inheritance.
        - outcome: → dropped because historical/contextual; no actionable move on the receiver side.

    - candidate: feedback-seeking behavior research note
        - location: lines 430-432
        - paraphrase: actively seeking feedback (especially negative) correlates with higher satisfaction, faster adaptation, lower turnover, higher performance ratings.
        - outcome: → dropped because it is empirical motivation, not a procedure. The seeking-out skill itself will live in chapter 12 (Get Going) where the book describes how.

    - candidate: modeling for kids and colleagues
        - location: lines 442-444
        - paraphrase: how you handle feedback teaches the people around you (children, direct reports, peers) how to handle feedback. Modeling is part of the stakes.
        - outcome: → dropped because it is a stakes-raising frame, not an actionable receiver move with its own signal.

    - candidate: digging for ponies
        - location: lines 450-459
        - paraphrase: receiving feedback is not always pleasant, but there might be a pony in there somewhere. Disposition.
        - outcome: → dropped because it is a disposition aphorism, not a procedure. The actual technique for finding the pony is "First Understand" (chapter 5, dedicated whole-chapter skills).

- Chapter 3: 1. Three Triggers That Block Feedback, lines 471-738

    - candidate: identify-which-trigger-is-firing
        - location: lines 503-527, "Three Feedback Triggers" section, with the smoke-alarm framing at lines 493-497
        - paraphrase: when feedback derails you, there are only three categories of trigger (truth, relationship, identity), each with a different remedy. Before responding, name which one (or which mix) is firing. The triggered reaction itself is the map that locates the source of trouble; do not suppress it without first reading it.
        - situation: you are in the grip of a triggered reaction to feedback (heart pounding, thoughts racing, defending/attacking/withdrawing) and you are about to either push the reaction aside and "stay professional" or act on it without diagnosis.
        - outcome: → promoted to identify-which-trigger-is-firing

    - candidate: triggers-as-map-not-obstacle
        - location: lines 493-497, the smoke-alarm metaphor
        - paraphrase: a triggered reaction is not just an obstacle to push past; it is information about what set it off. Suppressing it is like disconnecting the smoke alarm.
        - outcome: → folded into identify-which-trigger-is-firing. The disposition (read the alarm) and the procedure (categorize among the three) are one move; the disposition without the categorization yields no action, and the categorization presumes the disposition. Worked into the failure-mode and signal sections of that skill.

    - candidate: separate appreciation, coaching, evaluation (truth-trigger remedy 1)
        - location: lines 552-563
        - paraphrase: identify whether the feedback you want and the feedback you are getting are appreciation, coaching, or evaluation; the mismatch is its own source of failure.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 4 ("Separate Appreciation, Coaching, and Evaluation"), where the move gets its full treatment. This chapter only previews it.

    - candidate: first understand (truth-trigger remedy 2)
        - location: lines 569-584
        - paraphrase: before deciding what to do with feedback, work to understand what the giver actually means; pursue clarification of the specific behavior, situation, and recommendation.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 5 ("First Understand"), where the move is the chapter's spine. Previewed only here.

    - candidate: see-your-blind-spots (truth-trigger remedy 3)
        - location: lines 590-603
        - paraphrase: feedback that feels wrong may be wrong, or it may be in your blind spot; assume both possibilities and work to surface what others see that you cannot.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 6 ("See Your Blind Spots").

    - candidate: don't-switchtrack (relationship-trigger remedy 1)
        - location: lines 618-629
        - paraphrase: when relationship triggers fire, the receiver tends to drop the original feedback and substitute their own grievance about the giver, producing two parallel topics neither party hears. Disentangle and discuss separately.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 7 ("Don't Switchtrack: Disentangle What from Who").

    - candidate: identify-the-relationship-system (relationship-trigger remedy 2)
        - location: lines 635-647
        - paraphrase: feedback in a relationship is rarely the story of you or me; it is the story of the dynamic between us. Ask "what's the dynamic and what are we each contributing?" instead of trading blame.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 8 ("Identify the Relationship System").

    - candidate: learn-your-wiring (identity-trigger remedy 1)
        - location: lines 661-664
        - paraphrase: people are wired differently in baseline mood, swing, and recovery from feedback; knowing your own wiring explains your reactions and others' non-reactions.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 9 ("Learn How Wiring and Temperament Affect Your Story").

    - candidate: dismantle-distortions (identity-trigger remedy 2)
        - location: lines 670-677
        - paraphrase: identify the patterns by which your mind distorts and magnifies feedback; once aware, dismantle the distortion to engage with the actual content rather than your magnified perception.
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 10 ("Dismantle Distortions").

    - candidate: cultivate-growth-identity (identity-trigger remedy 3)
        - location: lines 683-693
        - paraphrase: shift from a fixed identity story (feedback is a verdict on what I am) to a growth identity (feedback is information about where I stand now and what to work on).
        - outcome: → deferred to chapter 11 ("Cultivate a Growth Identity").

- Chapter 4: 2. Separate Appreciation, Coaching, and Evaluation, lines 739-1099

    - candidate: sort-the-kind (appreciation / coaching / evaluation)
        - location: lines 780-799 (the three kinds named in the bar scenario), lines 805-846 (each kind defined), lines 874-905 (the "we need all three" table)
        - paraphrase: when feedback is on the table (incoming or sought), identify which of the three kinds it is — appreciation (I see you, you matter), coaching (here is how to grow, or here is something missing in our relationship), evaluation (here is where you stand against a standard). Each serves a different need; treating them as one category is the source of much receiver-side trouble.
        - situation: feedback is being given or asked for and you are about to react to it as one undifferentiated thing called "feedback" without naming which of the three is actually in play.
        - outcome: → promoted to sort-the-kind

    - candidate: diagnose-the-cross-transaction (kind-mismatch)
        - location: lines 970-994 (the "Beware Cross-Transactions" section, with April/Cody/Evelyn 0-for-3), and lines 999-1016 (the "always evaluation in coaching" structural mismatch with Elsie)
        - paraphrase: when feedback lands wrong despite both parties acting in good faith, the diagnosis is often that the kind you wanted and the kind you got are different — or the giver intended one kind and you heard another. Name the mismatch explicitly (giver gave X, you wanted/heard Y) before debating the content.
        - situation: a feedback exchange has just happened and you are dismayed, deflated, or more anxious than before. The content is not obviously wrong but it does not address what you came for, and you are about to either argue the content or suppress the dismay.
        - outcome: → promoted to diagnose-the-cross-transaction

    - candidate: negotiate-which-kind-you-need
        - location: lines 1031-1052, "Get Aligned: Know the Purpose and Discuss It," with the three alignment questions (1036-1042) and the receiver scripts at 1050 ("You're offering coaching, but it would help to get a quick evaluation," "You're saying this is coaching, but I'm hearing it as evaluation, too"). Closes with Elsie's case at 1052 (she actually wanted appreciation for a week of practice).
        - paraphrase: before or during a feedback conversation, surface which kind you want (and which kind the giver thinks they are giving) and negotiate explicitly when they differ. "Explicit disagreement is better than implicit misunderstanding." The receiver may need to take the bull by the horns and name the kind they actually need.
        - situation: you are about to enter (or are inside) a feedback conversation and you sense you and the giver are on different tracks about what kind of feedback this is, and you are about to leave the misalignment unspoken and walk out frustrated.
        - outcome: → promoted to negotiate-which-kind-you-need

    - candidate: evaluation-first sequencing
        - location: lines 1058-1069, "Separate Evaluation from Coaching and Appreciation," with the bugle-blast metaphor (1061), the performance-review scenario (1063), and the graded-paper analogy (1067, "the student will first turn to the last page to check their grade. Only then can they take in the instructor's margin notes").
        - paraphrase: evaluation is loud enough to drown out coaching and appreciation. Until the where-do-I-stand question is answered, coaching cannot land. As receiver: settle the evaluation question first (ask for it, separate it in time, or get the floor) before trying to absorb coaching layered on top.
        - situation: you are receiving (or about to receive) coaching while an unresolved evaluation question is live (am I on track? do I still have a future here?), and you are about to try to absorb the coaching on top of an unanswered evaluation, or attribute the coaching's failure to land to its content.
        - outcome: → promoted to settle-evaluation-first

    - candidate: appreciation has three qualities (specific, in receivable form, authentic)
        - location: lines 941-951
        - paraphrase: for appreciation to actually count for the receiver, three qualities are needed: it must be specific (not "good work!"), it must come in a form the receiver values (some hear it in words, some in trusted-adviser status, some in promotion), and it must be authentic (not performed to check a box).
        - outcome: → dropped because the chapter casts these as criteria for givers, and the receiver-side analog (notice when received appreciation lacks one of the three; ask for it in your own form) is too thin a procedure on its own. The receiver-side move is already covered by sort-the-kind (recognize that the appreciation you are getting is not landing) and negotiate-which-kind-you-need (ask for it in a form that lands). No distinct action/signal/failure that those two skills do not already supply.

    - candidate: evaluation shortfalls / "evaluative floor"
        - location: lines 907-918
        - paraphrase: removing evaluation altogether leaves a hole that receivers fill by reading coaching and appreciation as veiled evaluation. Receivers need an evaluative floor before they can take in the other two.
        - outcome: → folded into settle-evaluation-first. The "evaluative floor" insight is the same chapter argument that drives the evaluation-first sequencing skill: the absence of evaluation produces the same stuck state as a loud unfavorable evaluation. Captured in that skill's "When to reach for this" and "Failure mode."

    - candidate: there is always evaluation in coaching (structural)
        - location: lines 999-1016
        - paraphrase: every "here is how to improve" carries an implicit "so far you are not doing it as well as you might." The giver has only partial control over the evaluative echo; the receiver may funnel coaching into the evaluation slot regardless of intent.
        - outcome: → folded into diagnose-the-cross-transaction. The structural evaluative-echo is one of the two cross-transaction patterns the section names (the other being "I wanted X, got Y"). Captured in that skill as the second pattern of mismatch (giver intended coaching, receiver heard evaluation).

    - candidate: appreciation deficits / MADD
        - location: lines 944-945
        - paraphrase: over time, two-way appreciation deficits set in: each side feels unappreciated by the other.
        - outcome: → dropped because it is a relational diagnosis at the dyad level, not a moment-of-receipt receiver action with its own signal and failure. The corresponding receiver move (ask for appreciation in a form you can hear) is folded into negotiate-which-kind-you-need.

    - candidate: Luke and the gallery (entertainment is not feedback)
        - location: lines 850-868, the America's Got Talent sidebar
        - paraphrase: some feedback is performed for an audience other than you; recognizing the gallery (TV viewers, online commenters, talk-radio listeners) reframes the feedback as evaluation-as-spectacle, only loosely about you.
        - outcome: → dropped because the gate fails on action: the actual receiver-side action this implies (decide whether the feedback's primary audience is you or a gallery, and discount accordingly) is too situation-specific (public, mediated feedback) to generalize beyond the scenario. The structural insight is already covered by sort-the-kind (this is evaluation, performed for a third party) plus engaging-is-not-accepting (you can hear it without using it).
